<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-018-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 018 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC Professional  Oct 1989 v8 n11 p62(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Freeze, system manager! Apprehending a computer-crime suspect.andO;(the second of a two-part series, the first of which discussedcomputer crime and protection strategies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sidrow, Christina L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The apprehension of a computer criminal requires a clearunderstanding of the difference between usual and unusual computersystem activity, the identification of suspicious activity,investigation and accurate documentation of that activity forevidence (understanding of the evidence requirements of state andfederal law is vital), and use of that evidence in a police reportto support the accusation of the computer criminal.andP;  Tools formonitoring and identifying normal and unusual system activity on aDigital Equipment Corp VAX minicomputer running the VMS operatingsystem include SHOW USER/OUTPUT, SHOW SYSTEM/OUTPUT, the AccessControl List method of alarming, and accounting file monitoring.andO;A management-approved contingency plan should be in place fordealing with suspicious activity.andP;  Details of crime identificationand reporting are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialManagement of EDPComputer CrimesProceduresSecurityMonitors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>